# Icon Library Standard

- Always use `lucide-react` for icons in React components by default.
- Prefer importing icons directly from `lucide-react` (e.g. `import { Shield, FileText } from "lucide-react"`).
- Do not introduce additional icon libraries (e.g. Heroicons, Font Awesome) unless there is a strong, documented reason.
- If you need a custom icon:
  - First check whether a close-enough lucide icon already exists.
  - If not, implement it as a local SVG React component and keep it isolated to `components/icons` so the rest of the app still uses lucide icons.
- When creating reusable UI components that take an `Icon` prop, type it to accept lucide icons (e.g. `Icon: typeof Shield`) or a generic `ComponentType<{ className?: string }>` but continue to pass lucide icons from call sites.

## Example

```tsx
// ✅ Good: lucide-react
import { Shield, FileText } from "lucide-react"

export function Example() {
  return (
    <div className="flex gap-3">
      <Shield className="size-5" />
      <FileText className="size-5" />
    </div>
  )
}

// ❌ Avoid adding a second icon library for simple line icons
// import { ShieldCheckIcon } from "@heroicons/react/24/outline"
```

